A cool idea! I do have some tips that I think would help you obtain the look you are trying to achieve. Since fairies are not real, I am going off the image that comes to mind when I think of a fairy.
First off, the things I like. The nose highlight! it really makes it look dainty and gives a nice glow. Your freckles are gorgeous and fit the fairy them, so I'd say don't try to cover them up.
The lipstick is too frosted and gets lost in with the rest of your skin. I think a nude or light pink gloss would add a bit of color without taking attention away from your eyes.
The brows are also a little too bold for a fairy's. Fairies are wispy, airy; they flutter around and are weightless. Using less brow product and letting some individual hairs show will help. That doesn't mean don't do them at all, just go for a more natural look.
The eyeshadow is cool, but the yellow should be kept on your lid or lid to crease only as to minimize visual clutter. It will have more impact that way. The eyeliner wing also is very dramatic, thick, and angled. This is really good for some looks, but doesn't really fit in with this one.
I hope this helps!

I don't buy much high-end makeup that I regret, but I do regret a lot of my NYX stuff. Some of it is great, so that's why I continue to buy the brand. Sadly, a lot absolutely sucks...
* **NYX Liquid Suede in Vintage:** Just way too purple-toned, much more than it appeared in the tube. Smudges a lot and the paddle-applicator sucks. I also can't get over the sticky texture and bad smell.
* **NYX felt tip liner:** Oh god, worst pigmentation and ran out day one I used it. Stick with anything else...I was really looking forward to an affordable one, too.
* **NYX Wonder Pencil:** Don't bother using this on your waterline if you want it to stay more than 10 minutes. It comes off easily, has an overly-firm texture, and doesn't blend well either.
* **NYX Tres Jolie Liner:** It is good quality gel liner itself, but the sharpener doesn't sharper. I honestly just broke the tip every time I tried to use it, no matter at what angle or pressure. Therefore, I either put the product onto another eyeliner tip or don't use it at all.
